post_text:
The East Valley Middle School yearbooks have arrived!

We are ready to handout yearbooks to students who ordered and purchased 2019-2020 yearbooks. Thank you for your patience. We will distribute the yearbooks as a drive-thru process in front of the building. You will be asked to stay in your vehicle and we will bring you your book. Please remember this will take a little time and we will service vehicle by vehicle. You will be asked to sign that you received your yearbook so we have an accounting of each book. The distribution will happen Monday, August 10th, and Tuesday, August 11th. Please come during your assigned time and remain in your vehicle in line.

Monday, August 10:
9 am to 10 am: 2019-2020 Yearbook class (students enrolled in yearbook last year)
10 am to 12 pm: 2019-2020 8th grade class
12 pm to 2 pm: 2019-2020 7th grade class

Tuesday, August 11th:
9 am to 11 am for anyone who could not pick up on Monday.

Thank you for your patience and understanding during this time.

February Kind Kids Club at Otis Orchards
The Kind Kids Club worked on creating love bugs for our community helpers! Students also were able to keep one for themselves but many decided to give their love bug to someone in their family. A teacher read the book Be Kind, Pace Ambassadors made a thinking map with ideas that students got from the book and then students decided to accept the challenge of 100 acts of kindness in the month of February. We can't wait to see how these students spread kindness this month and every month!

post_text:
Trentwood Receives Over $4,000 from the Hagen Foundation
Trentwood’s 1st grade Teachers and Title Team received a $4138 grant from the Hagen Foundation to purchase FrontRow's all-in-one classroom audio systems to support our instructional goals. The necklace-style pendant teacher microphone makes instruction understandable throughout the room, while student microphones encourage participation and confidence. The digital filter means that students clearly hear instruction and peer collaboration above background noise.
THANKS, HAGEN FOUNDATION FOR SUPPORTING LEARNING!

The East Valley High School Knowledge Bowl team finished second place in the 2A division at the Eastern Washington Regional championship tournament. post_text:
East Valley HS FBLA Sending Twenty-Five to State
The Northeast Region of Future Business Leaders of America (FBLA) welcomed 400 students from across the Greater-Spokane area to take part in a wide variety of competitive events. General event areas include public-speaking, job interview, role-play, test-taking, and research presentations. Content areas in FBLA are wide-ranging in business, marketing, social sciences, technology, career acquisition, healthcare and many more.

The East Valley chapter qualified twenty-five students to compete in the state competition to be held April 8-11 at the Davenport Grand. Regional champions include James Roberts in Accounting I and Computer Problem-Solving, Ethan Downing in Business Law, Gwendolyn Skeen in Job Interview, and Carter Hosking, Ben Fetters, and Rodney McGee Sports in Entertainment Management. (February 6, 2020)

Better late, than never...

Trentwood 3rd Grade Field Trip to Mobius Science Center
On December 5th, Trentwood 3rd grade students went on a field trip to Mobius Science Center. Students had the opportunity to construct a bridge using toothpicks and gumdrops. They made a plan, created a bridge, tested it, and had the opportunity to make improvements. Students were also able to spend time trying to different activities available at the Science Center. Many students printed money with their picture on it, made race cars, created with blocks, experimented with a ball drop, and many other fun things! Thank you to our parent volunteers and EVEA for helping fund this amazing trip! (December 2019)

EVHS FBLA Officers Installed
The East Valley Chapter of FBLA (Future Business Leaders of America) installed new officers on Wednesday, November
20th. The dessert was held in the EVHS library and was attended by approximately 60 members, parents, and family
members. Chapter membership has increased considerably from last year, with the current count being 54 members.

Josh Strebeck, an EV grad of 2019 spoke to chapter membership and parents and explained how much FBLA helped him with getting started with his current career in technology where he works for CHAS Health. In addition, CHAS is paying for his post-secondary education. WOW!

The 2019-20 officer team is Danielle Hillyard – Co-President, R.J. McGee – Co-President, Carter Hosking – Vice-
President, Secretary – Jazmine McGee, Treasurer – Sawyer Tracht, Public Relations Officer – Leah Syverson, Melissa Bareand Everett Callihan – Sophomore Representatives, Dianna Demko and Jenna Browning Freshmen Representatives.

East Valley FBLA and Chief ’s Teddy Bear Toss Net New Record
Twenty members of East Valley High School’s FBLA chapter attended the Spokane Chief’s Teddy Bear Toss to help with
the collection of 8,604 (a new Chief’s record) stuffed animals to be given to Spokesman Review Christmas Bureau. FBLA
members get to go on to the ice, pick up stuffed animals, and load them into shiny, new Ford pickups. Then they go into
the underbelly of the Veteran’s Memorial Arena to count and bag ever last stuffed animal to be loaded on to large box
trucks. East Valley FBLA teamed with DECA students from North Central and Mt. Spokane High Schools. Thank you to
the Chief’s organization and Jay Stewart for the opportunity.

post_text:
Middle School PEP Students Keep Their Doors Open

The morning started off with meaningful discussions about life goals. What do you want to accomplish? In what areas do you want to be successful? What doors do you want to keep open?
The next step was to identify and elaborate on barriers that could stand in their way. What school related struggles could keep you from reaching your goals? What social distractions could lead you in the wrong direction? What emotional barriers could shut your doors?
After small group discussions, the students had to build Rube Goldberg type Marble Mazes to represent their path to success. The maze had to include 1 “door” representing a life goal. Additionally, it had 3 barriers that could “shut” the door and solutions to each barrier that lay in their path.
The morning ended with sharing and peer feedback. The students shared a strong sense of camaraderie built around shared goals.

Harmony Park Installation at East Farms!
Deona Behrens received the Hagan Foundation in December of 2018. Lucien Saurette took the lead on installation. His helpers were: Dave Fuller, Chris Gehrs, Ken Olsonberg and Kent Allen.
One day the holes were dug. The next day the equipment was put in the holes and stabilized. That afternoon the cement arrived. A few days later the safety fencing came down and students made beautiful music. We are one fortunate school! From Vision to Installation to Music Making!

post_text:
InTec Guest Speaker from WSECU ~ 10/17/2019
Today at InTec, students had an exciting and engaging lesson in cooperation with WSECU. Students were given various
sources in which they had to collaboratively apply analytical processing, critical thinking, mathematical skills and reading
comprehension to solve a Lockbox Challenge with Josh Bergman from WSECU. Through the information students determined the appropriate car to purchase from their team's scenario while taking into consideration mileage, insurance costs, style preference, and monthly payment. They had to calculate the correct lock combination to gather the additional information needed to the next step in their purchase decision.
A big thank you to Josh and WSECU!

Spokane Community College Career Day ~ 10/8/2019
Students from our AP Environmental Science class and Introduction to Agriculture class attended an Environmental Sciences Career Day at SCC. Students were exposed to a variety of careers within the natural resources pathway. Students were able to do a GPS scavenger hunt, tour the greenhouse and wrap a flower like a florist. In addition, they looked at GIS mapping and learned how arborists safely climb trees. It was a fun, educational day, for all who participated.

Rascal Rodeo ~ 9/28/2019 ~ This event was held in Coeur d’ Alene, Idaho on a snowy Saturday morning in September. These four FFA members helped with set up and clean up for the Rascal Rodeo event. During the event they helped individuals with disabilities experience rodeo events that have been adapted. All four of these young people got home in time to get ready to attend the homecoming dance. Such great kids!
Pictured below: Grace Ribbeck (Senior), and her horse Bobbie; Gwendolyn Skeen (Junior); Tiffany Altermatt (Freshman)and Chase Wiedmer (Junior)

post_text:
East Valley High School Community Forum
Students in Advanced Placement American Government and College in the High School American Government classes hosted a community forum, sponsored by The Liberty Lake Splash and Current news publications on Thursday, October 3rd at East Valley High School. The forum included candidates running for Spokane Valley City Council positions 2(Brandi Peetz and Michelle Rassmussen), 3 (Arne Woodard and Lance Gruel) and 6 (Tim Hattenberg and Bo Tucker). Students from both East Valley and University High School asked questions of each of the candidates. Questions included discussion about homelessness, affordable housing, the rate of domestic violence in Spokane and the issue of race in the county.
Following the forum, candidates running for fire commissioner introduced themselves and why they are running and East Valley students explained Initiative 976 and offered the pros and cons.
The event was open to the public and not only served to inform voters; but provided an opportunity for students to experience participatory democracy.

Financial Management at InTec
InTec staff was thrilled to have Eric Puthoff from STCU here on October 1st & 3rd to simulate how to budget and responsibility manage credit. Each student was given a "life" and had to create a balanced budget on the 1st day of presentations. There were many revelations about how expensive life was! On the second day, students participated as groups in answering general personal finance questions and dissolving current financial myths.

World Character Day at Otis Orchards!
For World Character Day 2019 Otis Orchards Elementary celebrated across two days to increase awareness and provide families an opportunity to participate. At school all students and staff created a school wide paper-chain of character uniting us in promoting and celebrating good character. Each individual class created chains that were then joined together linking us all together. The chain is being hung through the halls as a visual statement of good character. During the second day of the celebration, September 28th, students and their families showed their commitment to good character by completing three acts of kindness.

Kind Kids Club at Otis Orchards
Kind Kids club had an amazing first meeting at Otis Orchards! The program was started last year and the group has almost doubled in size this year! 45 students chose to sign the promise to be a kind kid. They painted three rocks and chose to keep one, give one to someone in the community and hide one outside at Otis. It is amazing to listen to these students' stories of how to show respect and ways they can spread kindness. It's going to be a great year with this club!

post_text: FBLA Kicks Off Year with FunBLAst at EVHS! Future Business Leaders of America began their recruiting season with a social event called the FunBLAst. There was Speed-Dating (speed-friending), Trivia Challenge, and Just Dance (dancing to videos with the Nintendo Switch). Kids had a great time just being together. FBLA meetings are on Late-Start Mondays at 9am in Room 227. ALL STUDENTS ARE WELCOME TO JOIN. As a student organization we focus on competition, community service, and having fun. Maybe FBLA would be a good fit for your student. If you have any questions, your student can stop by Mr. Bret Kiefer’s room (227) or he can be reached at kieferb@evsd.org.

post_text:
East Farms STEAM School!
How does a STEAM school welcome the new year?

With Camp STEAM!
*We teach our STEAM expectations which are built through our Positive Behavior Intervention Supports (PBIS) process
*We teach bus, lunchroom, playground, hall and bathroom expectations
*Camp Lutherhaven sends counselors to guide team building activities
*Our 6th graders go to Lutherhaven for outdoor/overnight camp

What a wonderful way to start the year!

Celebrations at Trentwood
Trentwood had a morning of celebration earlier this week! Superintendent Kelly Shea kicked off the celebrations by presenting Rachel Zender with a Jim Kuehnle Outstanding Educator Award.

Superintendent Shea also thanked retiring teacher Dennis Earling for his 41 years of service in education. Both Rachel and Dennis had family members join our small reception.

Congratulations to you both!

Five schools honored in new state recognition program - Our Kids, Our Future

Our Kids Our Future
June 6, 2019 at 8:00 AM ·

Over the past year, the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction, State Board of Education, and Educational Opportunity Gap Oversight and Accountability Committee created a new system of recognizing and celebrating schools’ achievement on the Washington School Improvement Framework (WSIF) measures. The new system places more emphasis on schools who are making progress closing opportunity gaps among student groups, as well as schools who have lower levels of achievement, but are seeing high levels of progress. post_text: The 4th Graders at Trentwood took a field trip to the Valley Heritage Museum! It was amazing! post_text: East Valley High School was recently designated as a Bronze Certified Washington Green School. Of the thousands of schools in the state of Washington, only 200 schools have been given this distinction. The award was given in recognition of the work that the East Valley Green Team has done with their environmental action program in the area of waste and recycling. Green Team members have reduced the amount of waste the school produces substantially by recycling cans and bottles, batteries, cables, cell phones, paper, cardboard and printer cartridges. Congratulations, Knights, for keeping your school GREEN!

Prime Time Family Reading with Spokane County Library District
Trent and Trentwood Elementary Schools collaborated with the Spokane County Library to do a special one night Prime Time Family Reading Event on Monday, May 13th at the Spokane County Library. Students and their families enjoyed pizza, salad and a drink prior to the event, which was provided through Title I Parent Involvement funds. They learned about all the special services offered at the library, got a library card, learned how to properly care for books, how to "read away" fines, got a preview of the County Library summer reading program, listened to a book and completed an "alien" craft. A good time was had by all!

post_text:
FBLA Takes Twenty to State
Smith and Strebeck qualify for Nationals
The largest ever contingent of FBLA members from East Valley High School competed at the State Leadership Conference in Bellevue on April 10-13. Twenty students competing in a variety of contests including public speaking, role play, and project presentations. The group left early Wednesday morning, enjoyed an outstanding keynote speaker at opening session Wednesday evening, competed Thursday and Friday, attended awards presentation Saturday morning, and were home by Saturday afternoon. Grace Smith and Josh Strebeck qualified for national competition. Grace Smith will compete in management information systems (MIS), and Josh Strebeck will compete in Help Desk. Nationals takes place from June 27 to July 3 in San Antonio, TX. While in Bellevue the kids attended workshops and watched finals presentations in other
events. Fun, however, was not in short supply as the competitors also found time to shop, attend a dance, sing karaoke, compete in trivia contests, and meet other students from across the state.

post_text:
Junior Achievement Finance Park
Money, Money, Money!!! This past March all 8th graders at EVMS participated in Junior Achievement USA’s Finance
Park financial literacy curriculum. The 2-3 week curriculum culminated with a field trip to the Shriner’s Event Center
where students were given real life scenario’s (Video) that they had to budget for and then shop and live out the budget. Students learned about loans, insurance, benefits, credit scores, childcare costs, housing expenses, etc. Students enjoyed the experience and come away with more appreciation for managing money. As one student put it after going through the activity, “I feel bad for my parents” to the nodding agreement of many of her peers.

GEAR UP Spring Break College Visits
This past spring break twelve 8th graders from EVMS National Junior Honor Society got to go on a 3 day 2 night trip to visit a variety colleges. The trip included visits to a two year college (North Idaho College), four year public universities (University of Idaho and WSU) as well as a small liberal arts school (Whitman College). Activities included presentations, student panels, a ropes/challenge course, meeting mascots, lot’s of walking and plenty of college dining hall buffets. Students had a good time and came away with more information and ideas for their future post-secondary options.

post_text: East Valley Middle school hosted its first ‘Find Your Fit Fair’ on March 20 in collaboration with the high school CTE programs, GEAR UP and some of the local colleges. All 8th grade students got a chance to learn about high school CTE programs and student organizations as well as some post-secondary education options. Not only did they get to learn about them but they got hands on experience during the fair. Teachers and students alike found it a resounding success!

The East Valley School District is currently in the process of hiring a new administrator to serve as the Principal of Trent Elementary. As part of this process we are seeking input from our parents and community members.

We would like to extend an invitation to all East Valley parents and community members to join us for a Question and Answer session at Trent Elementary on Thursday, April 25th from 5:00 pm -7:35 pm. During these Q & A sessions, you will be given the opportunity to ask questions of the three finalists for the position.

We are hopeful that you will accept our invitation to participate in the process for selecting the next administrator for the East Valley School District.

If you have any questions about the Q & A sessions please contact the East Valley Human Resources Department at (509) 924-1830.

EVHS History Bowl Captures 4th in State!
The East Valley High School History Bowl team competed at the Washington State History Bowl tournament in Silverdale, Washington and earned 4th place in the state. Students spent more than seven hours answering questions about World, United States and European history, in addition to current events and United States government. The team was composed of Captain Noah Haight, Zephrym Bush, Al Carlson and Gage Nielsen. They also enjoyed a visit to the Museum of Pop Culture and the USS Turner Joy. Thanks for representing East Valley and Eastern Washington!

Donkey Basketball at EVHS ~ On March 12th the East Valley High School FFA chapter hosted Donkey Basketball. This was a fundraising event for the chapter. There were four teams playing, a Student Team (wearing FFA shirts), a Staff Team (wearing black), and East Valley Alumni Team (wearing green) and an EVHS Administration Team [with one student teacher] (wearing white).
It was tough competition and all of the teams had support from the crowd. It was a true community event, one that we hope will continue in the future. The winner of the championship game was the EVHS Administration Team!

Middle Level PEP Students Aspire to EVHS Knowledge Bowl Team!
During mid-winter break 9 Middle Level PEP students and their parents traveled to Whitworth University to cheer on the EVHS Knowledge Bowl Team. We were impressed by the Knowledge Bowl Knights and look forward to joining their team in the near future. We also enjoyed a college tour, meant to heighten our enthusiasm for all things collegiate. Highlights included the university science labs, the recreation center, and a peek into dorm life. We ended our tour with a delicious lunch in the University Cafeteria.

post_text:
A small group of students decided earlier this year to create a "Kindness Club" at EVMS doing random acts of kindness for people at the school. They remain anonymous but wanted a way to bring kind and caring acts to people. They call themselves "The Hidden Knights."
In February, the same group made Valentine's treat bags for EVERY SINGLE student in the school with a kind message attached and hid them in over 500 lockers as a surprise. This group is pretty amazing and, best
of all, remains anonymous! Nobody knows who they are which is what they love best! It is truly random acts of kindness. This is an example of what they did for the staff today. They partnered with Starbuck's on Sullivan who donated coffee and treats for the staff. Way to go Starbuck's!!!
Students also wrote hand crafted thank you cards to every staff member at EVMS. They plan to tackle many projects the remainder of the year building positive culture at EVMS and in the community.

post_text:
Spokane County Library District’s ‘Reading Buddies’ Program at Trent
Trent has partnered with the Spokane County Library to bring, "Reading Buddies," to our school. Reading Buddies are people who love reading to and with kids and want to help them gain skills and develop a life long love of reading. Every Monday morning, during our district late start, 11 Trent students are paired with volunteers from the Spokane County Library. The volunteers share a book, play a game and provide a snack for their buddy. Trent is excited to be part of this wonderful Spokane County Library Program.

FBLA Knights Represent at Regionals ~ Qualify Twenty-Two for State

On Thursday, February 7th, 29 East Valley FBLA members competed at the Northeast Regional at Valley Assembly Church. Twenty-Two of the 29 students qualified for the state competition to be held in April 10-13 in Bellevue. Wow! Both Josh Strebeck and Jared Hathaway were district champions. (See total results below.)

Staffs, Admin, and Parents, thank you for supporting all of the competitors in their efforts to achieve and represent East Valley. In addition to the high school, I want the middle school and elementary schools to know how much I appreciate the jobs you do in sending great kids to EVHS. These kids' accomplishments are just another result of the great job we all do in East Valley School District. I am very proud of these kids, and I know you are too! Our chapter will continue to prepare to represent the EV Knights’ community at State!

post_text: EVHS History Bowl: Bound for State! ~ The East Valley High School History Bowl team has once again qualified for the Washington State History Bowl competition. The team, led by junior Noah Haight, has competed in both the Spokane History Bowl Tournament and the Eastern Washington History Bowl Tournament. Individual students have participated in a variety of events, and the following students have won awards: Zephrym Bush and Al Carlson – qualified for Nationals in the U.S. History Bee; Josh Doll was the champion of the JV History Bee, Braydon Mertens earned 2nd place, Taylor Voelker was named 3rd place, and Tim Stark earned 4th place. Good luck at State, Knights!

post_text: On January 30th, InTec and EVHS students joined students from 2 other school districts to attend a hands-on introduction to the HVAC, Electronics Engineering, Welding, Machining, and Electrical & Hydraulics programs at SCC. These career pathways have 100% employment upon graduation in high paying jobs with excellent benefits and the job demand is only growing. As a bonus, there are plenty of jobs right here in Spokane; however these jobs skills are also in demand nationwide for individuals who chose to move. The students were engaged, asked inquisitive questions and all seniors completed their SCC registration. By completing their registrations early, students are not committed to attending, but instead have early acceptance into the program of their choice if they choose to attend.

post_text: Trent held a, "Donuts for Dads," event on Friday, January 18th. This was a collaborative event with Trent’s Parent Teacher Association. The PTA purchased all the of the Donuts! 213 Dads, granddads and a few moms attended the event. Each attendee received a deck of playing cards, donated by Northern Quest Casino. Title I created a packet of playing card games that accompanied each deck of cards and demonstrated one of the games at the event. It was fun to walk around and see the Dad's playing cards with their student, as they enjoyed their donuts. What a "sweet" way to start the school day.

EVHS Choir and FBLA Give and Receive Holiday Cheer!

On December 11th the choir and FBLA partnered for their annual visit to Guardian Angel Home to sing Christmas Carols.
“What a great opportunity to get to know the wonderful residents of Guardian Angel. It is truly a Win-Win experience for all.” -Bret Kiefer (FBLA Advisor)

“Our trip truly encompassed the spirit of the holiday season, blending the experiences of the old with those of the young. It felt like we were all family, even though none of us were actually related. “ -R.J. McGee (Sr. at EVHS)

“I appreciated seeing the smiles of the peoples’ faces and listening to their stories about their lives.” -Isabelle Downing (Freshman at EVHS).

post_text:
East Valley High School’s Future Farmers of America (FFA) Greenhand Ceremony
Advisor Leah Lucero
There were 15 students who applied for the Greenhand FFA Degree and 13 were in attendance at our first Greenhand Ceremony. The application is one where the students had to demonstrate their knowledge and get signed off in the following areas: FFA Motto, Creed, Mission Statement, Jacket and Emblem. In addition they had to have a sufficient plan for a Supervised Agricultural Experience (SAE) and know the history of FFA, dating back to 1928. These students worked hard in three months to achieve this first of four degrees that can be earned in FFA. In addition to earning a certificate, each member earned their Bronze Greenhand Pin that can be worn on their FFA jacket. As their advisor I am so proud of these students and I am grateful for the support of their families and our school district.

There were 15 students who applied for the Greenhand FFA Degree and 13 were in attendance at our first Greenhand Ceremony. The application is one where the students had to demonstrate their knowledge and get signed off in the following areas: FFA Motto, Creed, Mission Statement, Jacket and Emblem. In addition they had to have a sufficient plan for a Supervised Agricultural Experience (SAE) and know the history of FFA, dating back to 1928. These students worked hard in three months to achieve this first of four degrees that can be earned in FFA. In addition to earning a certificate, each member earned their Bronze Greenhand Pin that can be worn on their FFA jacket. As their advisor I am so proud of these students and I am grateful for the support of their families and our school district.
